Group 32: Predicting Life Expectancy Using Several Variables.¶

Group members: Jiawei Huang, Wanying Zheng, Lucy Liu, Cong Cheng, Effie Wang

Introduction¶

Over the past century, the development and improvement of healthcare service, education, and living standards have become important factors in the global rise of life expectancy (O'Connor, 2022). However, there are more factors that affect life expectancy. Life expectancy is a very important and distinct measure that summarizes the overall health of a comunnity. According to a study that investigates mortality rate in separated age groups, the mortality rate of children younger than 5 years decreased from 1970 to 2016 while the mortality rate of adult deaths increased in each 5-year age bracket above the age of 25 years (MacroTrends, n.d.). In contrast to earlier decades, the distribution of annualized rates of change in age-specific mortality rates was different from 2000 to 2016 (MacroTrends, n.d.).

By understanding and gaining more insight from the relationship between life expectancy and its determining factors, health institutes and governments can consider more aspects when they decide how to improve people' life span.

Our study will investigate influences from economy, immunization, and diseases on life expectancy. We aim to build a strong predictive model to predict life expectancy based on some input variables.

Dataset¶

We're considering our sample to be what is available here https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kumarajarshi/life-expectancy-who?resource=download

The tidied data consists of 1649 observations. The following list below includes the predictors we selected and the response variable Life.expectancy.

Life.expectancy: Life Expectancy in age

Year: the data is choosen from 2000 to 2015, (data selection time also influence the life expectancy, to standardize orders of magnitude, we use Year = Year - 2000).
Status: Developed or Developing status
Adult.Mortality: Adult Mortality (per 1000 population)
infant.deaths: Number of Infant Deaths (per 1000 population)
Alcohol: Recorded per capita (15+) consumption (in litres of pure alcohol)
percentage.expenditure: The percentage of Gross Domestic Product spent on health per capita(%)
Hepatitis.B: Hepatitis B immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
Measles: Measles reported cases (per 1000 population)
BMI: Average Body Mass Index of population
under-five deaths: Under-five deaths (per 1000 population)
Polio: Polio (Pol3) immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
Total.expenditure: General government expenditure on health as a percentage of total government expenditure (%)
Income composition of resources: Human Development Index in terms of income composition of resources (index ranging from 0 to 1) Diphtheria: Diphtheria tetanus toxoid and pertussis (DTP3) immunization coverage among 1-year-olds (%)
HIV.AIDS: Deaths per 1000 live births with HIV/AIDS (0-4 years)
GDP: Gross Domestic Product per capita (in US$)
Population: Population of the country
Schooling: Number of years of Schooling(years)
thinness 5-19 years: Prevalence of thinness among children for Age 5 to 19(%)

One potential impact is that our model could help with health institute. By monitoring a region's data, health institutes can make plan to help improve people's life expectancy. Increase in life expectancy can benefit a region's economy because people live longer and able to work longer.

From Figure 3, there are some variables that have high correlation and linear relationship with others. There are also some variables appear to have no relationship, for example, the plot of variable Year and Alcohol show a cloud shape with no obvious pattern, indicating that there is no linear relationship between them. They have correlation of -0.113, which is very low.

Figure 4: Heat Map of Correlations between all Numeric Variables

Based on the heat map from Figure 4, we can see that percentage.expenditure and GDP have high correlation of value 0.96. Also, infant.deaths and under.five.deaths have correlation rounded to 1, which is a perfect positive correlation. This suggests that we might need to remove either percentage.expenditure or GDP, infant.deaths or under.five.deaths, in order to ensure our models meet the assumption of multicollinearity.

Summary for results so far¶

  • The original dataset contains 22 variables and 2938 observations in total.
  • We remove rows with NA values, modify and remove columns, we have 20 variables and 1649 observations left for analysis.
  • The response variable is Life.expectancy and there are 19 input variables including 18 numeric variables and 1 categorical variable.
  • We need to remove some variables to alleviate multicollinearity.

Plan for Next Section¶

  • We fit a full model with our selected 19 input variables from the preprocessing above.
  • We remove input variables that have large VIF to decrease multicollinearity in input variables.
  • We check for assumptions of linear regression models including multicollinearity, normality, and heteroscedasticity.
  • Also, we use Ridge regression to alleviate collinearity in input variables.
  • We select our best model using cross-validation with Ridge regression (smallest lambda = best model).
  • We calculate test RMSE of our models on unseen data (test set).
  • We will have 3 models: full model, reduced model, and Ridge model, we want to pick the one with lowest test error.

test_df <- anti_join(life_tidy,

Full model¶

Assumptions of Linear Regression Models¶

It is very important to check whether our models meet the assumptions of linear regression model, if assumptions are violated, then the results from the model are not trustworthy.

There are 4 assumptions for linear regression models:

  • Linear relation between input variables and response variable.
  • Error terms are independent and identically distributed (check for Heteroscedasticity).
  • Error terms are Normally distributed.
  • Not severe Mulitcollinearity.

Checking Heteroscedasticity for Full Model¶

We graphically diagnose heteroscedasticity by comparing the fitted values to the residuals.

In [37]:
options(repr.plot.width = 7, repr.plot.height = 7) 

#get list of residuals 
res <- resid(life_full_OLS)

#produce residual vs. fitted plot
plot(fitted(life_full_OLS), res, main = "Residuals vs Fitted")

#add a horizontal line at 0 
abline(0,0)

Figure 5: Residual vs Fitted Values Plot for Full Model

Heteroscedasticity occurs when the variance of the error terms are not constant for all data points. From Figure 5 above, we can see that the assumption of constant variance holds, residuals are randomly scattered around 0 and show no pattern.

Checking Normality for Full Model¶

We assess the normality assumption via $Q$-$Q$ plot.

In [38]:
options(repr.plot.width = 7, repr.plot.height = 7) 

#create Q-Q plot for residuals
qqnorm(res)

#add a straight diagonal line to the plot
qqline(res)

Figure 6: QQ Plot of Full Model

QQ plot is useful for checking if the residuals follow a normal distribution. If the data values in the plot lie on the 45 degree line, then this indicates the error terms are normally distributed. The data values on our Figure 6 QQ plot lie near the 45 degree line, this indicates that the error terms are normally distributed.

In [39]:
options(repr.plot.width = 7, repr.plot.height = 7) 

#Create density plot of residuals
plot(density(res),main = "Density Plot of Residuals")

Figure 7: Density Plot of Full Model

We create a density plot, which is useful for visually checking whether or not the residuals are normally distributed. A bell-shaped distribution of residuals indicates normality assumption of error terms is met.

Lambda hyperparameter optimization with Cross-Validation¶

Next, we find the optimal value of $\lambda$ (that corresponds to the best predictive performance) by carrying out a 10-folds cross validation.

In [56]:
set.seed(SEED)

life_cv_lambda_ridge <- cv.glmnet(
  x = glm_X_train, y = glm_Y_train,
  alpha = 0,  
  nfolds = 10, # add k-fold: 10-folds
  lambda = exp(seq(-15, 5, 0.1))
)
# life_cv_lambda_ridge$lambda.min

We visualize the results and find the value of $\lambda$ that minimizes the CV error and its associated mean squared error (MSE).

In [57]:
options(repr.plot.width = 7, repr.plot.height = 7) 
plot(life_cv_lambda_ridge, main = "Lambda selection by CV with Ridge\n\n")

Figure 11: Lambda Value Plot for Finding Optimal Value

In [58]:
# the lambda value corresponds to the lowest CV error:
#   we will use this opimal lambda to build final model.
life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge <- life_cv_lambda_ridge$lambda.min
life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge  # should name it best.lam

# log(life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge)
3.37201523413918e-06

The life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge value above is the optimal lambda value that corresponds to the lowest CV error. We will use life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge to produce our final model.

Final Model¶

We build our final model with optimal $\lambda$ value from cross-validaiton.

In [59]:
# ridge
life_ridge_min <- glmnet(
  x = glm_X_train, y = glm_Y_train,
  alpha = 0,
  lambda = life_lambda_min_MSE_ridge
)

Discussion and Conclusion¶

Summary and Impact

Through our study, we found 3 models, they are the full model, reduced model, and ridge regression model. They all have very close RMSE, which is a measure of a model's performance on predictions of unseen data. The full model has the lowest RMSE, but it violates the assumption of multicollinearity, so this decreases its reliability. The reduced model meets all assumptions of linear regression model, but it has higher RMSE than our ridge model. Our ridge regression model will be our best predictive model, because it has the second lowest RMSE and ridge regression can alleviate collinearity.

These findings allow us to make prediction on peoples life span or expectancy. Also, being able to make predictions on life expectancy allows governments or institutes to better design plans for public infrastructure and communities.

Improvements

The model could be improved by including more data points and variables. The raw dataset contains many rows with NA values and we need to remove these rows, and this decreases the number of avaliable data points for us to do analysis. Even though including more observations might be expensive, the resulting predictive model might be more accurate.

We used ridge regression, which is a shrinkage method that does not shrink parameters to 0 and select variables. We would like to try lasso regression in the future, because lasso does select variables and this might help reduce costs in building models.

In the future, we want to make inference on how to improve peoples life span which might potentially increase citizens satisfaction in life. Inference involves deeper understanding of input variables and their relationships with response variable.

Further Research

For future studies and research, we want to investigate the combine effects of the input variables on the response variable by including interaction terms in our models. We also want to find some potential confounding variables.
